{"edits":[{"content":"The target's forbidden cases breach STANDARD std-crit-design clause (2) — \"forbidden cases that are concrete, measurable outcomes of running the proposed experiment\" — because they rely on critic variants that cannot be produced or measured by rerunning the repository's validation harness. The harness evaluates a fixed set of critic configurations whose flag decisions are already recorded; it provides no mechanism to synthesize new critics with prescribed question-conditional flag rates. Forbidden case 1 requires \"two critic configurations with identical marginal (phi, psi) but different question-conditional flag rates\" — constructing such a matched pair is a generation problem, not a measurement performed by the harness. Forbidden case 2 requires \"a critic … with uniform question-level flag rates\" — again a synthetic critic that the harness cannot instantiate. Forbidden case 3 requires a critic with specified marginal stats and specified conditional alignment P(flag|majority-wrong) > 0.8, P(flag|majority-right) < 0.2; the harness cannot conjure a critic satisfying these joint constraints. Because each forbidden case presupposes the existence of critic variants the experiment cannot produce from the repository, the cases cannot be measured by rerunning the harness, violating both clause (2) and the final sentence of the standard. The prose_notes confirm this gap: the experiment \"uses three critic variants to decouple marginal from conditional alignment,\" but no procedure is given for generating them within the harness, and the standard explicitly forbids proposals whose forbidden cases cannot be measured by rerunning this repository's validation harness.","changed_fields":["target_content"]},{"content":"The forbidden cases are presented as measurable outcomes of running the validation harness, not as generation procedures. The harness records question-level flag decisions alongside majority correctness for each configuration, so the quantities P(flag|majority-wrong), P(flag|majority-right), and per-question flag rates are directly computed from existing logs. Forbidden cases 1-3 describe outcome patterns that would refute the claim if observed among the evaluated configurations; they do not require synthesizing new critics. The harness measures these conditional alignment metrics, and the cases falsify the conjecture if the measured outcomes fall within the stated bounds.","changed_fields":["target_response"]}]}